Narrative Log

Dev Log - 2026-05-14

Today was a boundary day again, but with a different center of gravity than yesterday.

The Flow Builder work set the tone first. The typed surface ADR, token-domain inventory, and research application note all pushed the same idea: if a surface is going to be reused, it needs a contract that names its inputs, its receipts, and its allowed vocabulary. That is not paperwork for its own sake. It is the difference between a surface that can be composed safely and one that only works as long as everyone remembers the unwritten rules.

The Obsidian retrieval work was the sharper correction. Workspace-local retrieval is exactly the kind of seam that can become ambiguous fast: was the content found, injected, routed, or merely implied? The repair and proof attempt forced that seam to become more concrete. The follow-up current-state update mattered for the same reason. Once a proof path exists, the short-horizon docs need to say what really happened, not what the system would prefer to believe happened.

The composer and upload routing fixes fit into that same line of work. If upload visibility is wrong or external provider image handling is unclear, the UI can create false confidence very quickly. Tightening those edges makes the surface more usable, but more importantly it makes it less misleading.

The daily insight generator added a second output path to the repo, but it did not really change the theme. It extended the same discipline into a new content surface: generation with a home, tests, and a directory that exists on purpose. The marketing claim role changes point in the same direction. Statements need to advertise what kind of statement they are making.

What changed underneath the surface is that the repo is leaning harder into explicit contracts and named evidence paths. That is a good direction for a system that wants to stay local-first and truth-bound. It reduces the amount of guesswork required to use the surface, and it reduces the amount of trust required to believe it.

The next useful step is straightforward: verify the repaired retrieval and upload paths live, then keep the typed-surface and insight-generator docs synchronized with whatever actually lands next.
